New research raises concern about the safety of permanent hair dye and chemical hair straighteners, especially among African American women. The study was published in the International Journal of Cancer.
Researchers looked at medical records and lifestyle surveys from 46,709 women between the ages of 35 and 74. Women answered questions about their use of hair dyes and straighteners. 
They found that women who used permanent hair dye or chemical straighteners were at higher risk of developing breast cancer.
Permanent hair dye use was associated with about a 7% higher risk of developing breast cancer among white women, whereas in black women that risk was about 45%. Hair products contain more than 5,000 chemicals, which can raise cancer risk. 
When it came to chemical straighteners, risk didn't vary by race. Both black and white women who used hair straighteners were about 30% more likely to develop breast cancer than those who didn't use the products. For the chemical straighteners, one of the big concerns is formaldehyde, which is a known carcinogen. The actual risk found for use of these hair treatments is quite low and much more research is needed to know for sure how risky these products are. No need to panic for now, just be aware of this possible association.... #breastcancerawareness

Read your own #Mammogram report. Here’s how to do it...
Learn about different types of mammograms, 2D vs. 3D, breast densities and Birads scores.
Start your mammograms at:
- 40 if you have no family history of breast cancer and have no symptoms - If you have family history of breast cancer, I recommend starting your mammograms 10 years prior to the age that your first degree relative was diagnosed with breast cancer.
- If you have a genetic mutation, you might need to start your mammograms as early as age 30. -Call your doctor if you develop any new breast changes (lumps, nipple discharge or retraction, skin changes, dimpling of the skin or unusual pain) 
#mammogramssavelives

October is breast cancer awareness month and it is my goal to teach every single one of you how to be your own breast advocate. NO woman should go through what I went through. I will do everything in my power to fight breast cancer one follower at a time. :)

THANK YOU for the outpouring of love, the flowers, text messages, phone calls and visits. My heart is full. I’m doing great and recovering well from my surgery but more importantly...
I SAVED  MY  OWN  LIFE  this past week. Here’s my story...
AGAINST EVERY DOCTOR’S ADVICE,  and even though I had NO family history of breast cancer, NO genetic mutations, NO cancer biopsies and NORMAL mammograms, ultrasounds and MRIs prior to surgery, I scheduled my own prophylactic bilateral mastectomy. I chose this very aggressive surgery just based on my elevated lifetime risk for developing breast cancer. I had 2 precancerous biopsies in my life (9 years and 7 months ago) and I had very dense breast tissue.  I used a formula to calculate my lifetime risk of breast cancer. Surprisingly my risk came back very high (37-50%). I made a decision NOT to wait for cancer and I decided to remove my breasts. (Thanks to @nasseri.ent and @aminmirhadi for pushing me to do this). Everyone else around me thought I was crazy. 
I had my surgery last week and everything went well. 
Yesterday, to everyone’s surprise, my path report came back positive for stage 1 BREAST CANCER. 😱Wait!!! What????Me???? 😱I was shocked. For months, breast specialists and radiologists told me I was OK, that I didn’t need this surgery and that my decision to have a mastectomy was an aggressive one. Well, my “aggressive” decision saved my life. I’m so glad I’ve been documenting my story on camera. My goal was to educate every woman about breast cancer screening, mammogram, ultrasound, MRIs, genetic screening, importance of family history and evaluation of a lifetime risk of breast cancer. I did this surgery to avoid cancer, not knowing that I already had stage 1 breast cancer in my right breast. Scary, isn’t it??
Once I recover, I will release my story. But one thing I know for sure.... BE YOUR OWN ADVOCATE in life!!! I did it and it saved my life.😢

I have so much to teach you about breast health and I cannot wait to share my journey with all of you. I will be back in a few weeks. Till then...🙏🏻💖
(Just to clarify, I don’t have breast cancer)

Can’t get pregnant?? Here’s some quick and easy info you can use to find the cause. 👫Most (85%) couples will get pregnant within a year of trying.
👫Infertility is the inability to get pregnant after 12 months of regular unprotected sex. 👫It affects 10%-15% of couples. 👫Go down this list with your primary care or gynecologist before visiting an infertility specialist: 
1- Is the egg reserve normal? Test: AMH, Day 3 FSH/E2
2- Check a hormone panel (Thyroid panel/prolactin) and an STD panel. 
3-Make sure the semen analysis is normal. Poor sperm quality/count/motility=No pregnancy. 25% of all infertility is caused by sperm defect. 
4- Is the uterus normal? Fibroids? Bicornuate uterus?Test: pelvic ultrasound.
5- Is the uterine cavity normal? Any septum? polyps? Adhesions? Test: HSG
6- Are the tubes blocked? Test: HSG. A Hysterosalpingogram
helps us evaluate the patency of the fallopian tubes. The HSG is usually scheduled between days 6 and 13 of the cycle - after bleeding and before ovulation. 
7- Endometriosis? Any history of painful periods? Painful sex? It affects 10 percent of women. One of the top causes of infertility in the world.
8- PCOS? History of irregular cycles? Acne? Facial hair? Male pattern hairloss? Get a pelvic ultrasound to look for PCOS  ovaries and check Testosterone, DHEAS, 17hydroxyprogesterone. 👫If 1-8 are all normal, then
9- Check both partner’s chromosomes 
10- Consider a full autoimmune workout. 👫Majority of infertile couples will fall into one of the above categories. Hope this helps. Good luck.
#infertility #infertilityawareness #lovemypatients

Many of us spend months planning a wedding (me🙋🏻‍♀️) but when it comes to starting a family, most couples have not heard of pre-pregnancy genetic testing. @joojoopresh and all future moms, this one’s for you. :)
🧬If you are planning on getting pregnant in the near future, ask your doctor for Genetic Testing. 🧬The Family Prep Screen is an affordable DNA test and is covered by most major health insurers. It can assess a couples’ DNA for heritable diseases with 99.9% accuracy.
🧬Children inherit identifiable characteristics from their parents: eye color, nose shape, hair texture, and countless others. They can also inherit genetic diseases, even if neither parent appears to have symptoms. 🧬Many genetic diseases are hidden in our genetic code.
🧬When a person tests positive for the genes of a particular disease, but does not actually have the disease, that person is said to be a carrier. If two carriers of the same disease have a child together, that child has a 25% chance of developing the disease.
🧬Family Prep Screen Test can help parents and future parents detect whether they are carriers of genetic diseases before they get pregnant, so that they can better plan for the future of their family.
🧬Your doctor will take only a small blood sample from you and your partner and send the samples to the lab. In less than 2 weeks, you will receive both of your results in a single report.
🧬If you and your partner discover through genetic testing that you are both carriers for the same genetic disease before pregnancy or early into pregnancy, then you may wish to consult with your doctor to discuss your options and make the right decisions for your family.
🧬Some couples can minimize their risk of passing on harmful genes by working with a fertility specialist. With in-vitro fertilization, you may use a preimplantation genetic diagnosis. This is a technique in which a specialist grows several embryos in the lab and then implants the one(s) with the healthiest genes in your womb.
🧬Don’t forget to get tested!

Can breast implants cause cancer?
👙The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has identified a possible association between breast implants and the development of breast-implant associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma (BIA-ALCL), an uncommon cancer of the immune system. 👙About 400,000 women get implants annually in the US, 75% for cosmetic reasons and most of the rest for breast reconstruction after cancer surgery.
👙The FDA believes that women with breast implants that have textured surfaces have a very low but increased risk of developing BIA-ALCL. 👙 Most confirmed cases of BIA-ALCL have occurred in patients with textured surface implants.
👙Some other countries have banned or restricted sales of certain textured implants.
👙Further research is needed to understand the relationship between the condition and breast implants.
👙As of Sept. 30, the FDA had identified 457 cases of implant-related lymphoma and nine deaths worldwide.
👙Educate yourself about breast implants before agreeing to surgery.
👙If you have breast implants, there is no need to change your routine medical care and follow-up. You should expect swelling and pain immediately after surgery. 👙If you notice changes in the way your breast looks or feels after you recover from surgery, including swelling or pain around the implant, be sure to talk to your health care provider about the possibility of BIA-ALCL. #breastimplants
